\section{Introduction}

Last time we saw the terrible family dynamics caused by Sarah's plan
which caused the birth of Ishmael to Abraham and Hagar. Here we see the
birth of Isaac --  the son of promise -- and briefly examine the family
dynamics, focusing most of our time on the sacrifice of Isaac.
Next time we will look at the next generation -- Jacob and Esau -- from
Gen 25:12 -- Gen 35.

\subsection{The birth of Isaac Gen~21:1--7}

God fulfils his promise at the specified time\ldots

\red{Note:} Get someone to read \red{Gen~21:1--7}

\red{Q:} What do Abraham's actions at Isaac's birth say about his faith?

\red{Q:} Remembering that God instructed Abraham and Sarah to name this
child Isaac -- ``He laughs'' -- what how should we interpret Sarah's
response at his birth?

\subsection{Family Feud Gen~21:8--21}
Jealousy erupts again when Sarah sees Ishmael laughing (Gen~21:9). She
asks Abraham to banish Hagar and Ishmael (Gen~21:10) Abraham is displeased
(Gen~21:11) but God instructs Abraham to do so because Isaac is the son
of the covenant (Gen~21:12). God says he will make a nation out of
Ishmael as well (Gen~21:13), so Abraham banishes Hagar and Ishmael
(Gen~21:14.) God makes certain they are cared for (Gen~21:15-21).

\red{Q:} What continuing consequences do you see of Sarah's plan?

\red{Q:} How does God use them to further His will and show His
righeousness?


\subsection{Abraham deals righteously with Abimelech Gen~21:22-34}
Abimilech realizes that Abraham is blessed by God (Gen~21:22). The
two men make a covenant to deal kindly with one another (Gen~21:23--24).
They handle a dispute well (Gen~21:25--32). Abraham continues to worship
the Lord (Gen~21:33-34).

\red{Q:} How does Abraham demonstrate his faith in this section?

\red{Q:} What effects did it have on Abimelech? What lessons are there
for us here?

\subsection{The sacrifice of Isaac Gen~22}

\red{Note:} Get someone to read \red{Gen~22:1--19}

\begin{itemize}
  \item The section is framed as a test (Gen~22:1).
  \item God asks the unthinkable - to sacrifice the child of
  promise (Gen~22:2).
  \item Abraham obeys immediately (Gen~22:3--5).
  \item Isaac carries the wood, Abraham the knife (Gen~22:6)
  \item Isaac questions Abraham about the lack of a sacrifice,
  Abraham responds, ``God will provide for himself the lamb for
  a burnt offering, my son.''  The NET notes tell us, ``The Hebrew
  is literally `will see for himself.' The construction means
  `to look out for; to see to it; to provide.' ''
  \item Abraham prepares to obey and is stayed by an angel, noting
  a ram in the thicket, which Abraham sacrifices (Gen~22:13--14)
  \item Abraham names the place ``The Lord (\emph{Yaweh}) will
  see/provide \\  (\emph{Yi ra ah})''.
  
