\section{Abraham chooses a wife for Isaac (Gen 24)}

\begin{itemize}
\item Abraham did not want Isaac marrying a Canaanite woman (Gen 24:3).
\item He gets his servant to pledge to find a wife for Isaac from among
his relatives (Gen 24:4).
\item The servant makes the journey and finds Rebekah, the daughter of
one of Abraham's nephews (Gen 24:15).
\item The servant convinced Rebekah's father, Bethuel, and brother,
Laban, to pledge her to Isaac (Gen 24:34-51).
\item The servant returns with Rebekah in time to
comfort Isaac over Sarah's death (24:67).
\end{itemize}
\section{The death of Abraham (Gen 25)}
\begin{itemize}
\item Abraham married Keturah after Sarah's death (Gen 25:1) and had other 
sons.

\item He gave gifts to the sons of Keturah and his concubines while he
was living (Gen 25:6).

\item He left all the inheritance to Isaac (Gen 25:5).

\item Abraham died at age 175 (Gen 25:7). Isaac and Ishmael buried him
with Sarah in the cave of Machpelah near Mamre (Gen 25:9).

\item After Abraham's death, God blessed Isaac (Gen 25:11).
The scriptures do not report further contact
or strife between Isaac and his brothers.
\end{itemize}
